{{for|the Maltese archbishop|George J. Caruana}} [[File:George Caruana - Filosofia.jpg|thumb|''Filosofia'' (1869) by George Caruana]]
{{Infobox person | name = George Caruana | birth_date = 1831 | birth_place = [[Victoria, Gozo]] | death_date = May 27, 1872 | death_place = [[Malta]] | occupation = [[Philosophy]] }}
'''George Caruana''' (1831–1872) was a Maltese minor [[philosopher]] mostly interested in [[epistemology]]. He held the Chair of Philosophy at the [[University of Malta]] (1859–72).<ref>{{harvp|Montebello|2001|loc=Vol. I, p. 69}}</ref>
==Life== Caruana was a diocesan priest. He was born in [[Victoria, Gozo]] in 1831, and dedicated his relatively short life to academic work. He studied at the bishop’s seminary in [[Gozo]], and then at the [[Gregorian University]] in [[Rome]], [[Italy]], from where he graduated as Doctor of Ecclesiastical Studies. Back in the [[Maltese islands]], in 1858 Caruana was appointed Rector at the bishop’s seminary of [[Malta]]. Here he taught philosophy and [[mathematics]]. A few months later, in 1859, he was appointed Professor of the Chair of Philosophy at the [[University of Malta]]. His teaching compliments here were various: intellectual philosophy, [[moral philosophy]], and [[metaphysics]]. During the same time, he was also member of the Committee of the [[National Library of Malta]]. Caruana occupied the Chair of Philosophy for thirteen years, until his premature death. He died on May 27, 1872. His funeral oration was delivered by fellow-philosopher [[Saviour Cumbo]].
==Extant work== Only one work of Caruana is as yet known to exist. It is simply called '''''Filosofia''''' (Philosophy).<ref>{{harvp|Montebello|2001|loc=Vol. I, p. 167}}</ref> The work is still in manuscript form.<ref>[[National Library of Malta]], [[Valletta]], MS. 1334.</ref> It is written in Italian, and contains 184 folios in Caruana’s own handwriting. The document is divided into an introduction, chapters, and paragraphs.
Caruana deals with a number of themes, namely, knowledge, truth, nature, conscience, sensibility, imagination, intellect, intuition, judgement, discourse, memory, words, and such like subjects. All are discussed in a philosophically clear and argumentative way.
